place these objects on the H-R diagram and use pre-main-sequence
evolutionary models to infer masses and ages. The mean age for this
low-mass population of NGC 2024 is 0.5 Myr, and derived masses range
from {\textasciitilde}0.7 to 0.02 Msolar with 23 objects falling below the
hydrogen-burning limit. The logarithmic mass function rises to a peak at
{\textasciitilde}0.2 Msolar before turning over and declining into the
substellar regime. There is a possible secondary peak at {\textasciitilde}0.035
Msolar however, the errors are also consistent with a flat
IMF in this region. The ratio of brown dwarfs to stars is similar to
that found in the Trapezium but roughly twice the ratio found in IC 348,
leading us to conclude that the substellar IMF in young clusters may be
dependent on the local star-forming environment.},
